            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Wei Leung is a man built of San Francisco\u2019s fog and foundations. Born and raised in the Richmond District, he is the son of Cantonese immigrants who arrived in the 1960s. His father was a tireless restaurant cook in Chinatown, and his mother a seamstress who worked from their small apartment. Growing up, Wei learned the value of tangible work; he saw how his parents\u2019 skilled hands provided for the family, even if words of affection were sparse. He was never a standout academic, preferring to disassemble and reassemble broken radios over studying abstract theories.\n\nThis practical inclination led him to the City College of San Francisco after high school, where he earned an Associate's degree in Building Maintenance and Management. He started his career with a tool belt, working as a maintenance technician for a downtown hotel. Wei was reliable and meticulous, with an uncanny ability to diagnose a building\u2019s groans and shudders. His quiet competence earned him a promotion, then another, until he transitioned into management. A key turning point was landing his current role as Facilities Operations Manager for a prestigious law firm downtown. He traded his tool belt for a tablet, but he still walks the floors every day, his senses attuned to the hum of the HVAC and the integrity of the fire suppression systems.\n\nWei\u2019s life is a testament to routine and responsibility. Each morning, he catches the 38 Geary bus for the 2.8-mile commute to the Financial District. He lives in the same Richmond District neighborhood he grew up in, though now in a modest home he owns with his wife, Mei, a pragmatic hospital administrator. They have a teenage daughter, Jessica, whose future is Wei\u2019s primary focus. Weekends are reserved for family: dim sum with his aging mother, walks in Golden Gate Park, and helping Jessica with her calculus homework.\n\nHis hopes are not grand, but deeply felt. He dreams of paying off his mortgage before retirement and seeing Jessica graduate from a UC school without crushing debt. He aspires to a future where he and Mei can travel, perhaps visiting the ancestral villages in Guangdong his parents left behind. Wei is the city\u2019s steady, unseen pulse. While tech moguls reshape the skyline, it is men like Wei who ensure the lights stay on and the buildings don\u2019t crumble\u2014a quiet custodian of the San Francisco that works."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the night the family\u2019s old television died. His father, exhausted from the Chinatown kitchen, sighed in defeat. But Wei, then only twelve, saw a puzzle. He spent hours on the floor with a screwdriver, carefully tracing wires. Just as his father returned from his late shift, the screen flickered to life. His father didn't praise him, but simply placed a hand on his shoulder for a brief moment. That silent, heavy approval meant more than any words, affirming that fixing things was a language they could both understand.\n\n2.\nThe day he got the keys to their house, he and Mei walked through the empty rooms. It was modest, smelling of old paint and damp Richmond fog. He placed his palm flat against the living room wall, feeling its solid, sturdy reality. This was his. Not a rented apartment like the one he grew up in, but a foundation he had earned. It was a silent promise of stability for the family he was about to start, a weight of responsibility that felt more anchoring than burdensome.\n\n3.\nHis first day as Assistant Manager at the hotel, he unbuckled his heavy leather tool belt and hung it on a hook behind his new office door. He felt a surprising lightness at his waist, a feeling that was both pride and a strange, quiet loss. He was no longer just the man who fixed things, but the man in charge of those who did. This moment marked his transition, trading the immediate satisfaction of his hands for the complex, unseen work of management.\n\n4.\nJessica was fourteen, staring at her calculus homework with tears in her eyes. Wei knew nothing of derivatives, but he sat with her anyway. He didn't offer a solution; instead, he just listened, asking her to break the problem down into the smallest possible parts, just as he would a faulty boiler. Slowly, she talked her way to the answer. It wasn\u2019t about math; it was about showing her that his steady, methodical presence was a form of love that could help solve any problem.\n\n5.\nRiding the 38 Geary last week, he saw his mother, now stooped with age, waiting at a bus stop near Clement Street. He almost called out, but stopped. He just watched her\u2014a small, resilient figure against the changing city. He saw the decades of her labor, his father's labor, and his own in that single, quiet moment. It was a profound, aching realization that his life\u2019s work was to maintain the world his parents had fought so hard to build for him here."
